our account information with your customer number and zip code account   zip code  my account users guide faqs customer support or browse topics search for answers advanced search collapse use advanced terms yes   no    using advanced search the advanced terms capability of our compliance expert puts the power of our lucenebased search engine at your fingertips it provides you with multiple options for a more powerful and efficient search experience importantly though by choosing to use advanced terms you render the dropdown filters in the advanced search null hence you only can use advanced terms or use the preset filters and keywords but you cannot use both in the same search about modifiers and boolean search connectors using the term modifiers below you will be able to construct a rich query to find results for your search first some important background a query is broken up into terms and operators there are two types of terms single terms and phrases a single term is a single word such as test or hello a phrase is a group of words surrounded by double quotes such as hello dolly multiple terms can be combined together with boolean operators to form a more complex query each term can be further revised by a term modifier wildcard searches you can perform a wildcard search within a single term but not within a phrase the single character wildcard search looks for terms that match that with the single character replaced for example to search for text or test you can use the search tet multiple character wildcard searches looks for zero or more characters for example to search for test tests or tester you can use the search test you can also use the wildcard searches in the middle of a term tet note however that you cannot use a  or  symbol as the first character of a search fuzzy searches fuzzy searches help find words that sound the same but are spelled differently such as roam and rome words that have alternative spellingslabor and labour those that are misspelled and those that include a base word but include prefixes andor suffixes search results for the word plan will include preplan and planning to do a fuzzy search use the tilde symbol  at the end of a singleword term for example to search for a term similar in spelling to roam use the fuzzy search roam proximity searches you can find words that are within a specific distance away from one another to perform a proximity search use the tilde symbol  followed by the number of words that can separate your search words for example federal corporation will find federal deposit insurance corporation term boosting if there is a term in your search query of particular importance you can increase its relevance to the query using the carat operator  if you want to indicate that the word treasury is more important in your search use the query treasury guidance the higher the boost factor the more relevant that term will be in your result set boolean operators of course the search query also supports the standard set of boolean operators to specify how your search terms should be combined the default operator is or so if there is no operator specified the query engine assumes an or the or operator links two terms and finds a matching document if either of the terms exist in a document the and operator matches documents where both terms exist anywhere in the text of a single document the not operator excludes documents that contain the term after not it cannot be used with just one term specified in the search the near operator links terms and finds a matching document if the terms are located within five words grouping we support using parentheses to group clauses to form subqueries this can be useful if you want to control the boolean logic for a query federal and guidance or regulation hide add a search term or and not near topic content type other government documents news my resources search by publication date publication date publication year publication month publication i