ttlement order  ferc ¶  at p  citing pjm interconnection llc  ferc ¶  at p   settlement order  ferc ¶  at p   id  see supra note    settlement order  ferc ¶  at p  “in section  of the energy policy act of  congress noted the concerns voiced by the governors of the new england states regarding the licap mechanism and declared that the commission should carefully consider their objections”   id p   trailblazer pipeline company  ferc ¶   order on reh’g  ferc ¶   trailblazer  the four approaches laid out in trailblazer are   commission renders a binding merits decision on each contested issue  commission approves the settlement based on a finding that the overall settlement as a package is just and reasonable  commission determines that the benefits of the settlement outweigh the nature of the objections and the interests of the contesting party are too attenuated and  commission approves the settlement as uncontested for the consenting parties and severs the contesting parties to allow them to litigate the issues raised  settlement order  ferc ¶  at p  citing trailblazer  ferc ¶  at   settlement order  ferc ¶  at p   see isone april   reply comments at  contending that “every detail” of the settlement “was critical to one or more of the negotiating parties” and that “changing one aspect of the settlement package will likely cause a chain reaction that could easily lead to the demise of the settlement leaving new england without a solution for what most if not all agree is a serious problem”  settlement order  ferc ¶  at p   highislandoffshore system llc  ferc ¶   hios  id p   see eg petal gas storage llc  ferc ¶  at p   southern lng company llc  ferc ¶  at p   southern carolina gas transmission corp  ferc ¶  at p    see southern  ferc ¶  at p   remand order  ferc ¶  at p   morgan stanley  s ct at   n commission may look at the “totality of the circumstances” not just the three factors – continuing ability of utility to provide service excessive burden on consumers undue discrimination – once identified in sierra   see arizona corporation commission et al v ferc  fd  dc cir  modifying the terms of earlier settlements despite presence of mobilesierra public interest standard not to protect one party from an “improvident bargain” but rather to prevent “the imposition of an excessive burden” on third parties quoting northeast utils serv co v ferc  fd   st cir  devon power llc  ferc ¶   remand order norris dissenting in part save to research folder saved to choose a folder or add to a new folder email to a friend your email address  your name  to email address  message  print article additional resources federal energy regulatory commission ferc elibrary newsletters leads to insight research  news search browse topics browse by book products energy compliance plans  pricing register for a free trial subscribe now contact sales about us company mission contact us customer support copyright  thompson information services privacy policy  terms  conditions x please log in to ask the expert user idemail password remember me forgot your password